  "learnings_before": "- Both valproate and carbamazepine are guideline‑consistent first‑line options for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; selection is guided by drug availability, tolerability, and the need for laboratory monitoring.\n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are acceptable for focal epilepsy but must be avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or hypersensitivity.\n- Before any change of therapy, clinicians must obtain baseline safety labs (ALT/AST < 2 × ULN, platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within normal limits) and, when feasible, a serum level of the current AED.\n- Dose optimisation is performed first: if the current dose is < 20 mg/kg/day for valproate or < 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine and seizure control is suboptimal, the dose should be titrated upward in 25‑50 mg increments every 1–2 weeks before considering drug substitution or adjuncts.\n- Exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone in children with cerebral palsy are not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; they require confirmation (e.g., seizure diary or video‑EEG) before altering the regimen.\n- The decision hierarchy is: (1) confirm seizure‑free status (≥ 6 months) and adherence ≥ 80 %; (2) verify normal safety labs; (3) maintain the current regimen unchanged; (4) if either seizure control or labs are inadequate, proceed to dose optimisation; (5) if optimisation fails, consider switching to valproate (after normal LFTs) or adding levetiracetam as an adjunct.\n- Valproate is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies at ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; carbamazepine is similarly stocked at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; levetiracetam is 2–3 × more expensive and often unavailable, so it is reserved for documented valproate intolerance or failure.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable; it may be used in spastic cerebral palsy only with close monitoring for sedation, otherwise it is avoided.\n- Initiation of valproate requires baseline liver function tests and ammonia; if ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or ammonia is elevated, valproate should be deferred and an alternative AED chosen.\n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window (20–30 mg/kg/day) and safety labs are normal, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current dose without escalation or adjunct addition.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Phenobarbital is the most commonly used first‑line AED for infants with focal seizures; when seizures persist despite an adequate phenobarbital dose, clinicians typically add carbamazepine rather than discontinue phenobarbital.\n- Valproate is avoided in neonates and infants younger than 3 months because of increased risk of hepatic toxicity; carbamazepine is preferred as the adjunctive agent in this age group.\n- Children with Down syndrome have a higher incidence of drug‑induced rash; aromatic AEDs such as carbamazepine are used cautiously, and valproate is favored for generalized seizure types.\n- In resource‑limited settings the cost hierarchy drives drug choice: phenobarbital (cheapest) → carbamazepine (slightly more expensive) → valproate; levetiracetam and newer agents are rarely prescribed unless first‑line drugs fail or are unavailable.\n- Therapeutic dosing ranges used in Ugandan paediatric practice: carbamazepine 15–35 mg/kg/day (titrated by 2–3 mg/kg every 1–2 weeks); valproate 20–30 mg/kg/day (titrated by 5–10 mg/kg every 1–2 weeks).\n- Baseline safety labs (ALT/AST, CBC, ammonia) are ordered before initiating valproate; for carbamazepine baseline liver tests are obtained when feasible, but clinical monitoring for rash and ataxia is often relied upon when labs are unavailable.\n- Carbamazepine induces hepatic CYP enzymes and lowers phenobarbital serum concentrations; after starting carbamazepine, phenobarbital dose is reassessed 5–7 days later and adjusted as needed.\n- The step‑wise treatment algorithm in district hospitals: verify adherence and seizure‑free status ≥ 6 months → if controlled, continue current regimen; if uncontrolled, optimise current dose; if still uncontrolled, add a second inexpensive AED (carbamazepine first, then valproate) while maintaining phenobarbital; proceed to third‑line agents only after failure of the combination.\n- Empirical data from Ugandan paediatric epilepsy clinics show that the most frequent escalation for infants on phenobarbital with refractory focal seizures is the addition of carbamazepine (≈ 68 % of cases).\n- Abrupt discontinuation of phenobarbital is avoided; when tapering is required, the drug is reduced over at least 2 weeks to prevent withdrawal seizures.\n- Children with cerebral palsy or significant motor impairment are monitored closely for exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone, which are not automatically attributed to AED toxicity without confirmatory seizure diaries or video‑EEG.\n- In the presence of congenital heart disease, clinicians prefer AEDs with minimal cardiac effects; phenobarbital and carbamazepine are favored over agents that may require intensive cardiac monitoring.",
